You assume that the title of Sam Smith’s long-awaited second album – The Thrill of It All – is a slightly weary one, weighing up the emotional cost of partying.
Actual thrills are scarce on these 10 tracks, which fulfil the brief of following up a hit album with a bankable sequel.
Pray finds Smith struggling with agnosticism but resorting to more gospel choirsBut this music is ever so easy on the ear.
Why would any pop star in their right mind ever take a sonic risk, when the rewards for moping by numbers are so vast?
For all his protestations to the contrary on Baby, You Make Me Crazy, Smith is very sane.